\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
The contribution of seed size and number to local adaptation in 
\emph on
Arabidopsis thaliana
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Thomas James Ellis, Chris Oakley, Froukje Postma, Jon Ã…gren
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
As populations adapt to their local environment, we expect selection to
 tune investment in different life history stages to maximise reproductive
 success.
 We large reciprocal transplants at two sites over five years we examined
 the extent to which components of fecundity contribute to local adaptation
 in 
\emph on
Arabidopsis thaliana
\emph default
.
 We found strong selection for both fruit number per plant and seed number
 per fruit.
 Fecundity components were strongly positively correlated with one another,
 as well as with survival,but we found no trade-off between fecundity and
 seed mass.
 QTL analyses found that fecundity components share a common genetic basis,
 and that both antagonistic and conditionally neutral allelic effects contribute
 to local adaptation.
 At both sites, the fittest individuals were able to invest in all fitness
 traits, suggesting that variation in fitness is driven primarily in differences
 in overall resource availability.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Local adaptation is the process by which populations evolve in response
 to the specific selection pressures in their native habitat 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "williams1966,kawecki2004conceptual"

\end_inset

.
 A crucial aspect of this process is tuning the investment of resources
 into different life-history stages to match local conditions, such as adult
 growth, offspring number and offspring size 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "lack1947significance,stearns1992"

\end_inset

.
 Given that the amount of resources available is always finite, there must
 necessarily be trade-offs in the amount of resources which can be allocated
 to different traits, relected in negative correlations between fitness-related
 traits 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "stearns1992,roff2002life"

\end_inset

.
 Such trade-offs are a major selective force shaping variation in nature
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "hereford2009quantitative"

\end_inset

.
 One the other hand, when variation in overall resource availability is
 large, this can overwhelm variation in allocation strategy, leading to
 positive correlations between traits 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "vannoordwijk1986"

\end_inset

.
 These two scenarios are important for local adaptation because they can
 either constrain or facilitate the response to local selection pressures.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Maximising reproductive output is vital for maximising evolutionary fitness.
 For plants, fecundity depends on the number of seeds produced, and this
 can be achieved by increasing fruit number or increasing seed number per
 fruit 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "silvertown1989paradox"

\end_inset

.
 Seed number is a highly plastic trait that can vary enormously in response
 to resource availability and abiotic pressures, even among individuals
 with identical genotypes 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "puckridge1967competition,lloyd1987selection,sadras2007evolutionary"

\end_inset

.
 This predicts that selection should act to allow plants to optimally utilise
 the resources available to maximise total seed production.
 Studies of local adaptation in plants typically focus on either fruit productio
n or total seed production as a measure of fecundity (e.g.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "latta2009testing,hall2010local,fournier2011map,hancock2011adaptation,agren_genetic_2013"

\end_inset

), yet seed production per fruit has received relatively cursory attention
 (e.g.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "agren_reciprocal_2012,hall2006divergent"

\end_inset

).
 It is therefore unclear the extent to which different components of fecundity
 contribute to overall differences in reproductive success, nor whether
 they constrain or complement one another.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Investment in fecundity may also show complex relationships with other fitness-r
elated traits.
 Energy allocated to reproduction reduces that available for investment
 in defence against parasites and predators, or abiotic stressors such as
 cold tolerance 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "stearns1992,roff2002life"

\end_inset

.
 In plants, growth depends on meristems, which can develop into either vegetativ
e or reproductive tissue.
 Since these outcomes are mutually exclusive, there is a necessary trade-off
 between reproduction and further growth 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "geber1990cost"

\end_inset

.
 Similarly, providing additional resources to offspring through increased
 seed size may increase the fitness of the offspring 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "venable1992size,leishman2000evolutionary"

\end_inset

.
 Comparisons across species have confirmed a negative correlation between
 seed mass and number 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "salisbury1942,moles2004seedling,moles2006seed,sera2004number"

\end_inset

.
 However, intraspecific variation in seed mass is dwarfed by variation in
 seed number 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "harper1970"

\end_inset

, and aside from crop species 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "gambin2010resource"

\end_inset

, no consistent positive or negative relationship has been found between
 seed size and number within populations 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "silvertown1989paradox,venable1992size"

\end_inset

.
 Interactions between fitness traits will depend strongly on the environmental
 conditions, and need to be examined in the specific local context.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Important insight into the process of local adaptation can be gained by
 examining the genetic architecture underlying adapative traits 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "merila1999genetic,mauricio2001mapping"

\end_inset

.
 Firstly, information about the number and location of quantitative trait
 loci (QTL) with detectable effects on phenotypic variation can reveal the
 extent to which QTL for fitness-related traits are found in the same regions
 of the genome, and hence whether relationships between phenotypes share
 a common genetic basis.
 Secondly, the change in phenotype associated with alleles at these loci
 can be used to infer the genetic mechanisms that have contributed to trade-offs
 in fitness at the level of contributing loci.
 For example, are fitness differences driven by antagonistic pleiotropy,
 where the local allele is favoured and the non-local allele disfavoured?
 Alternatively, do we observe conditionally neutral effects, where local
 alleles confer an advantage in one environment, but have no effect at other
 sites 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "kawecki2004conceptual,anderson2011evolutionary"

\end_inset

? Because allelic effects depend strongly on the environment it is essential
 to assess their contribution under field conditions 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "anderson2013evolution"

\end_inset

.
 Reciprocal transplant experiments using mapping populations at the sites
 of origin are an excellent tool to investigate the architecture of local
 adaptation in situ.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this study we investigate the adaptive significance and genetic basis
 of components of fecundity in 
\emph on
Arabidopsis thaliana
\emph default
.
 We carried out reciprocal transplant experiments using a large RIL population
 and the parental lines at the source sites in central Sweden and Italy
 over five years.
 Previous work has shown that the parental lines are locally adapted, and
 identified winter survival in Sweden and fruit production in Italy as major
 determinants of fitness 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "agren_reciprocal_2012"

\end_inset

.
 Although not the focus of their study, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "agren_reciprocal_2012"

\end_inset

 also presented preliminary data suggesting that the local genotype produced
 more seeds per fruit than the non-local genotype, and hence that fruit
 number alone is likely to be an underestimate of total fecundity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, we explicitly examine the contribution of two components of fecundity,
 fruit number and seed number per fruit, to local adaptation.
 Specifically we ask: (1) what is the relative strength of selection acting
 on each trait? (2) Are there trade-offs between components of fecundity
 or (3) between fecundity and survival or seed size? (4) Do we find large-effect
 QTL for fecundity components, and do they share a common genetic architecture?
 Our results reveal that genetic variation in seed traits makes an important
 contribution to local adaptation though effects on fecundity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Materials and methods
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Data collection
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Data on survival, fecundity and fitness are taken from experiments in 2010
 and 2011 described in detail by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "agren_genetic_2013"

\end_inset

.
 Briefly, we set up reciprocal transplant at sites at RÃ¶dÃ¥sen in central
 Sweden and Castelnuovo di Porto in central Italy 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "agren_reciprocal_2012"

\end_inset

.
 At each site, we transplanted seedlings of parental genotypes from both
 sites and 398 recombinant inbred lines (RILs) derived from these parents
 in autumn.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In each following Spring we scored plants for three fitness metrics used
 by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "agren_genetic_2013"

\end_inset

: (1) survival to reproduction, (2) number of fruits for per plant that
 survived to reproduction (a measure of fecundity), and (3) number of fruits
 per planted seedling (a measure of overall fitness).
 For subsequent analyses we used the mean of trait values across individuals
 of the same genotype.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At each site-year experiment we also collected a single mature but unopened
 fruit, from between 79 and 189 parental plants and between 1917 and 2359
 RIL plants.
 We stored seeds in paper envelopes at room temperature until counting.
 We subsequently counted and weighed all seeds per fruit on a Metler Toledo
 AT261 balance.
 We then calculated mean seed mass as the mass of all seeds in a fruit,
 divided by the total number of seeds.
 We estimated mean values for each line in each site-year experiment as
 the mean across all individuals of the same genotype.
 After excluding lines with fewer than three replicate individuals per line,
 we were able to estimate values for seed number per fruit and seed mass
 for between 340 and 389 RILs for each site-year experiment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We also used these data to estimate proxies for total fecundity and total
 fitness.
 We estimated seed number per reproductive plant as the product of fruit
 number per plant and seed number per fruit.
 Likewise, we estimated seed number per planted seedling as the product
 of fruit number per planted seedling by fruit number per plant.
 Since we did not have data on seed number per fruit for all individuals
 for which data on fruit number was available, we instead multiplied line-mean
 seed number by individual fruit number values.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Data manipulations and all subsequent statistical analyses were performed
 in RStudio 0.99.1266 using R 3.3.1 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "r_core_team,rstudio"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Fitness differences between parental lines
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To assess the relative importance of fitness components to adaptive differentiat
ion we first examined which traits best explain overall differences in fitness
 between local and non-local genotypes.
 We calculated selection coefficients in terms of overall fitness (seed
 number per seedling), as well as two components of fecundity (fruit number
 per reproductive plant and seed number per fruit) and survival.
 We calculated selection coefficients as 
\begin_inset Formula $s=1-w_{A}/w_{B}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{A}$
\end_inset

 is the fitness of the local genotype and 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{B}$
\end_inset

 that of the non-local genotype 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "gillespie2010population"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We estimated confidence intervals around estimates of 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 by parametric bootstrapping.
 We resampled the data for each experiment with replacement 1000 times and
 calculated selection coefficients for each bootstrap sample.
 We estimated 95% confidence intervals for each coefficient as the 25th
 and 975th quantiles of these values.
 We declared selection to be significantly different from zero if confidence
 intervals did not overlap zero 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "nakagawa2007effect"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Correlations between traits
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To assess the strength of trade-offs among traits we calculate Spearman's
 rank correlation coefficient, 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

, between RIL means for each site-year combination.
 We examined relationships between three pairs of traits: (1) components
 of fecundity (fruit number per reproductive plant and seed number per fruit),
 (2) survival and fecundity (seed number per reproductive plant), and (3)
 fecundity and investment in offspring (seed number per reproductive plant
 and seed mass).
 We performed analyses for data for each site-year experiment separately.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A small number of lines appeared to be outliers that showed consistently
 showed low fecundity, but unusually high seed mass (figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:scatter-plots"

\end_inset

).
 To exclude the possibility that these lines could unduly inflate correlation
 coefficients we repeated the analyses for fecundity and offspring investment
 excluding lines with mean seed mass greater than 35mg.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
QTL mapping
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We used the R/qtl package in R to map QTL for four traits: seed mass fruit
 number per reproductive plant, seed number per fruit and seed number per
 reproductive plant 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "broman2009guide,r_core_team"

\end_inset

.
 We performed mapping for RIL mean data for each site-year experiment separately.
 We used Haleyâ€“Knott regression using genotype probabilities of the genetic
 markers and pseudomarkers in gaps >2 cM 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "haley1992simple"

\end_inset

.
 We performed a two-QTL scan of the genome with 10,000 permutations of the
 phenotypic data to determine 5% LOD-significance thresholds for inclusion
 of QTL and epistatic interactions 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "broman2009guide"

\end_inset

.
 Based on these thresholds, we used R/qtl's automated stepwise model selection
 procedure to identify significant additive QTL and epistatic interactions.
 We first applied a quantile normal transformation to phenotypes before
 model selection.
 Finally we used ANOVA on untransformed data to fit the multiple QTL model
 and calculate effect sizes with respect to the Swedish allele, as well
 as the proportion of the total phenotypic variance explained by each locus.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We considered QTL identified for different sites, years or traits to be
 map to the same genomic region if the maximum-likelihood estimate of their
 positions were within 2cM of each other, or if the 95% Bayesian credible
 intervals for these estimates overlapped.
 This approach simplifies interpretation of QTL results, but risks losing
 information about individual genuinely distinct, but nearby QTL.
 This can be justified via the principle of Occam's razor; it is unnecessary
 to posit a a model with two QTL if it does not explain the data any better
 than a model with a single QTL.
 To aid interpretation we also excluded 'poorly-defined' QTL whose credible
 intervals for QTL position were less than 1/4 the length of the shortest
 chromosome (15.2cM; 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "agren_genetic_2013"

\end_inset

) from further analysis, because such QTL provide little information about
 position.
\end_layout

