\begin_layout Section
Discussion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This study investigated natural genetic variation for fecundity and its
 components among wild accessions and a recombinant inbred line population
 of 
\emph on
A.
 thaliana
\emph default
.
 Our results show that differences in overall seed number per plant between
 local and non-local genotypes are driven by differences in both fruit number
 per plant and seed number per fruit.
 We found strong positive correlations between components of fecundity and
 between fecundity and survival to reproduction, traits that represent major
 components of overall fitness.
 Despite this, we found little constraint of seed mass on fecundity.
 Large-effect QTL for total fecundity could be explained by QTL associated
 with one or both components of fecundity.
 Local alleles tended to favour the local genotype, with positive effects
 acting through both fecundity components.
 Together, these results indicate that the process of local adaptation in
 
\emph on
A.
 thaliana 
\emph default
involves maximising fitness in many fitness traits, with little evidence
 of trade-offs between traits, and that these trends are reflected at the
 genetic level.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We found contrasting patterns of the contribution of fecundity to fitness
 at the two sites.
 In Italy, differences in fecundity explain most of the differences in fitness
 between parental lines (figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:selection"

\end_inset

, see also 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "agren_reciprocal_2012"

\end_inset

).
 The advantage to the local genotype through fruit number per plant was
 approximately twice as large as that on seed number per fruit.
 Nevertheless, the mean selection of 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{s}=0.37$
\end_inset

 through seed number per fruit represents strong selection, and is of similar
 magnitude to values compiled by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "endler1986"

\end_inset

 for fecundity traits in other systems.
 By including information on seed number we are able to explain a substantially
 greater fitness difference between the parents in all years in Italy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Sweden, differences in fecundity contribute considerably less to differences
 in fitness than do differences in survival to reproduction 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "agren_reciprocal_2012"

\end_inset

.
 This is reflected in only weak selection on fecundity components in Sweden,
 which in one case significantly favoured the non-local genotype.
 The relative importance of fecundity components varied between years, with
 fruit number per plant explaining overall fecundity differences in 2011
 and 2012, and seed number per fruit explaining fecundity differences in
 2010 and 2014.
 As such, information on seed number allowed us to detect fecundity diferences
 between the parents in two additional years, that would not have been found
 had we considered only fruit number per plant alone.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Reproduction requires enormous investment in resources, and as such we would
 expect to find trade-offs between fecundity and other fitness traits.
 In fact, we found consistent positive relationships between fecundity component
s, and between fecundity and survival, regardless of site.
 This suggests that variation in fecundity between RILs is driven primarily
 by variation in the overall amounts of resources available to invest in
 all traits 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "vannoordwijk1986"

\end_inset

, with the fittest lines able to increase fruit number, seed number and
 survival.
 This does not mean that variation in allocation strategy does not exist,
 simply that any trade-offs between traits are overwhelmed by variation
 in resource availability.
 We found only weak or non-significant correlations between fecundity and
 seed mass.
 It thus appears that investment in seed mass puts negligible constraint
 on fecundity in 
\emph on
A.
 thaliana 
\emph default
despite substantial variation in resource availability.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
QTL analyses revealed that patterns of phenotypic variation in fecundity
 and its components are reflected in the genetic architecture of these traits.
 Of the loci with significant effects on each trait the local allele was
 associated with an increase in fecundity in all but one case (figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:effect-sizes"

\end_inset

).
 This effect was clearer in Italy than Sweden, where fecundity contributes
 more strongly to fitness than in Sweden (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "agren_reciprocal_2012"

\end_inset

.
 It was also clearer for fruit number per plant than for seed number per
 fruit, refelecting the stronger selection observed on fruit number (figure
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:selection"

\end_inset

).
 Furthermore, the majority of loci with a significant effect on overall
 fecundity showed significant positive effects on both components of fecundity
 (figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:effects-by-trait"

\end_inset

).
 This indicates that the positive relationships observed between phenotypes
 are reflected in the allelic effects of the underlying loci.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Combining data from multiple years in our QTL analyses provided substantial
 additional insight into the allelic effects of adpative loci.
 When we consider data for each experiment separately, most QTL clusters
 were only identified in a single experiment (figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:QTL-cluster-positions"

\end_inset

, tables S5-7).
 Moreover, these analyses identifed evidence for trade-offs between sites
 at only three loci (F2:2, F5:5 and T5:4).
 When data for multiple years are combined we found that most loci have
 significant effects across years that are too subtle to be detected in
 any single year (figures 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:effect-sizes"

\end_inset

 and S4).
 This allowed us to identify three loci with significant trade-offs for
 fecundity and both components, and five additional loci with evidence for
 trade-offs for one or both components of fecundity.
 For those loci with no globally significant effect on fecundity or its
 components, the effect sizes are generally in the direction favouring the
 local allele (figures 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:effect-sizes"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:effects-by-trait"

\end_inset

).
 It is therefore likely that antagonistic pleiotropy makes a greater contributio
n to adpative differences between genotypes than our data imply, but that
 these effects are below the threshold of statistical significance.
 This general difficultly of detecting antagonistic pleiotropy has been
 noted for other systems 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "e.g. "
key "kawecki2004conceptual,anderson2013genetic"

\end_inset

.
 These data highlight the value of multi-year studies in evaluating the
 effects of QTL to the process of adaptation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In conclusion, this study demonstrates that both fruit number per plant
 and seed number per fruit contribute to differences in fitness between
 local and non-local genotypes in 
\emph on
A.
 thaliana
\emph default
.
 We found no evidence for trade-offs between fecundity components, but rather
 that selection favours genotypes which are able to invest increased resources
 in across fitness traits.
 An interesting corollary of this finding is that it suggests that fecundity
 and survival traits are only the proximate causes of variation in fitness
 in a given environment, and that the ultimate driver of local adaptation
 is selection for some as-yet unmeasured trait related to resource use or
 efficiency.
 If true, this would suggest that the shared genetic basis among fecundity
 components and other traits 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "agren_genetic_2013"

\end_inset

 are in fact due to correlation with QTL for this putative trait.
 Nevertheless, an understadning of the proximate and ultimate causes of
 variation in fitness is vital to obtain a complete picture of the process
 of adaptation.
\end_layout

